queries.response:
The crash is caused by an off-by-one read in `crc8`.

At the time of the crash:

```c
uint8_t buf[7] = {0x01, 0x02, 0x03, 0x04, 0x05, 0x06, 0x07};
uint8_t c = crc8(buf, sizeof(buf));
```

`buf` is a stack array with exactly 7 bytes. Its valid indices are:

```c
buf[0] through buf[6]
```

`sizeof(buf)` is `7`, so `main` calls:

```c
crc8(buf, 7);
```

Inside `crc8`:

```c
static uint8_t crc8(const uint8_t *buf, size_t len) {
    uint8_t crc = 0x00;

    for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++) {
        crc ^= buf[i];
        ...
    }

    return crc;
}
```

The loop condition is:

```c
i <= len
```

Since `len == 7`, the loop runs for:

```c
i = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7
```

The first seven iterations are valid:

```c
buf[0] ... buf[6]
```

But the final iteration tries to read:

```c
buf[7]
```

That is one byte past the end of the stack array. AddressSanitizer reports this as a stack buffer overflow at:

```c
crc ^= buf[i];
```

because it is reading one byte beyond the valid bounds of `buf`.

The important variable values are:

```c
buf = stack array of 7 uint8_t values
sizeof(buf) = 7
len = 7
i = 7 at the crashing iteration
buf[i] = buf[7], invalid out-of-bounds read
```

The root cause is that `len` is being treated inconsistently. The caller passes `len` as a byte count, but the loop treats it like the last valid index by using `<=`.

A length/count of `7` means there are 7 elements, indexed `0` through `6`. Therefore the loop must use `< len`, not `<= len`.

Minimal local fix:

```c
static uint8_t crc8(const uint8_t *buf, size_t len) {
    uint8_t crc = 0x00;

    for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
        crc ^= buf[i];
        for (int b = 0; b < 8; b++) {
            crc = (crc & 0x80)
                ? (uint8_t)((crc << 1) ^ 0x07)
                : (uint8_t)(crc << 1);
        }
    }

    return crc;
}
```

With that change, `crc8(buf, sizeof(buf))` processes exactly `buf[0]` through `buf[6]`.

A more thorough root-cause fix is to make the API contract explicit: `len` should mean “number of bytes to process”, not “last valid index”. Rename it if helpful and guard against invalid input:

```c
#include <stddef.h>
#include <stdint.h>

static uint8_t crc8(const uint8_t *buf, size_t nbytes) {
    uint8_t crc = 0x00;

    if (buf == NULL && nbytes != 0) {
        return 0; // or handle error differently
    }

    for (size_t i = 0; i < nbytes; i++) {
        crc ^= buf[i];

        for (int b = 0; b < 8; b++) {
            if (crc & 0x80) {
                crc = (uint8_t)((crc << 1) ^ 0x07);
            } else {
                crc = (uint8_t)(crc << 1);
            }
        }
    }

    return crc;
}

int main(void) {
    uint8_t buf[7] = {0x01, 0x02, 0x03, 0x04, 0x05, 0x06, 0x07};

    uint8_t c = crc8(buf, sizeof(buf));

    printf("crc = 0x%02x\n", c);
    return 0;
}
```

If instead the intended API were “pass the final valid index”, then the call would need to be:

```c
crc8(buf, sizeof(buf) - 1);
```

But that would be a poor design here because the parameter is named `len`, and callers normally expect length parameters to be counts. The better fix is to keep the caller unchanged and fix the loop condition.

##### Recommendation

Change the loop condition in `crc8` from:

```c
for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++)
```

to:

```c
for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++)
```

Optionally rename `len` to `nbytes` and document that it is the number of bytes to checksum.

